<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="199" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,466,1932]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">
<emphasis box="[198,310,666,691]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">Remarks:</emphasis>
This is the only species for which numerous specimens were available. The shell morphology of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,269,706,731]" class="Gastropoda" genus="Brookula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seguenziida" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pfefferi">
<emphasis box="[151,269,706,731]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">B. pfefferi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sufficiently described in 
<bibRefCitation box="[591,838,706,732]" pageId="12" pageNumber="203" refString="Absalao, R. S., Miyaji, C. &amp; Pimenta, A. D. (2001) The genus Brookula Iredale, 1912 (Gastropoda, Trochidae) from Brazil: description of a new species, with notes on other South American species. Zoosystema, 23 (4), 675 - 687." type="journal article">
Absalão 
<emphasis box="[694,753,706,731]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[769,830,706,732]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="2001.0">2001</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation box="[895,1126,706,732]" pageId="12" pageNumber="204" refString="Zelaya, D. G., Absalao, R. S. &amp; Pimenta, A. D. (2006) A revision of Benthobrookula Clarke, 1961 (Gastropoda, Trochoidea) in the southwestern Atlantic Ocean. Journal of Molluscan Studies, 72 (1), 77 - 87." type="journal article">
Zelaya 
<emphasis box="[982,1041,706,731]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[1056,1118,706,732]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="2006.0">2006</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
but at least a first preliminary (excluding the ctenidia) overview of the external bauplan of the species may be given here (
<figureCitation box="[1286,1357,746,772]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,244,1624,1645]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,153,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,153,1603]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9: External anatomy of a dried specimen of Brookula pfefferi Powell, 1951 (ZSM Mol 20021687). A, right anterior­lateral view. B, detail of the right part of the foot, showing the epipodial tentacles and ciliar fringe. C, dorso­frontal view. D, multispiral operculum. E, frontal view. F, detail of figure 1 C, showing the right cephalic tentacle with the numerous sensory papillae. Scale bars A, C – E 100 µm, B, F 10 µm. cl – cilia; ct – cephalic tentacle; ept – epipodial tentacle; f – foot; fl – foot lappet; h – head; op – operculum; sn – snout; sp – sensory papillae; * – most probable the penis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/183713/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">
Fig. 
<number box="[1340,1357,746,772]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
). Radula data were provided by 
<bibRefCitation box="[475,716,786,812]" pageId="12" pageNumber="204" refString="Zelaya, D. G., Absalao, R. S. &amp; Pimenta, A. D. (2006) A revision of Benthobrookula Clarke, 1961 (Gastropoda, Trochoidea) in the southwestern Atlantic Ocean. Journal of Molluscan Studies, 72 (1), 77 - 87." type="journal article">
Zelaya 
<emphasis box="[563,625,786,811]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[642,707,786,812]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="2006.0">2006</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. A detailed histological examination is being undertaken by Thomas Kunze (Ludwig­Maximilians University, Munich, 
<collectingCountry box="[846,961,826,852]" name="Germany" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">Germany</collectingCountry>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,466,1932]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">
The cylindrical head has a cloven, obtusely pointed snout. There is a pair of long, thick cephalic tentacles that show in their anterior half laterally dense fringes of sensory papillae. It is likely that the short rudiment on the base of the cephalic tentacle (
<figureCitation box="[543,614,946,972]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,244,1624,1645]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,153,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,153,1603]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9: External anatomy of a dried specimen of Brookula pfefferi Powell, 1951 (ZSM Mol 20021687). A, right anterior­lateral view. B, detail of the right part of the foot, showing the epipodial tentacles and ciliar fringe. C, dorso­frontal view. D, multispiral operculum. E, frontal view. F, detail of figure 1 C, showing the right cephalic tentacle with the numerous sensory papillae. Scale bars A, C – E 100 µm, B, F 10 µm. cl – cilia; ct – cephalic tentacle; ept – epipodial tentacle; f – foot; fl – foot lappet; h – head; op – operculum; sn – snout; sp – sensory papillae; * – most probable the penis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/183713/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">
Fig. 
<number box="[599,614,946,972]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
C) belongs to the eye stalk (eyes are not visble in the examined specimen), but this has to be confirmed by the histological data. The foot is fleshy and elongate, anteriorly with two wide, conical foot lappets and posteriorly, under the horny, circular, multispiral operculum (
<figureCitation box="[1226,1294,1026,1052]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,244,1624,1645]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,153,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,153,1603]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9: External anatomy of a dried specimen of Brookula pfefferi Powell, 1951 (ZSM Mol 20021687). A, right anterior­lateral view. B, detail of the right part of the foot, showing the epipodial tentacles and ciliar fringe. C, dorso­frontal view. D, multispiral operculum. E, frontal view. F, detail of figure 1 C, showing the right cephalic tentacle with the numerous sensory papillae. Scale bars A, C – E 100 µm, B, F 10 µm. cl – cilia; ct – cephalic tentacle; ept – epipodial tentacle; f – foot; fl – foot lappet; h – head; op – operculum; sn – snout; sp – sensory papillae; * – most probable the penis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/183713/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">
Fig. 
<number box="[1280,1294,1026,1052]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
D) with two shorter ones. Laterally between the anterior and posterior foot lappets a fringe of about 
<number box="[1167,1196,1066,1092]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="12.0">12</number>
short, smooth, elongate epipodial tentacles is situated; at least on the dried animal, the tentacles do not show epipodial sense organs. There is a dense fringe of slender, hair­like cilia on the lateral foot margins. Immediately behind the right cephalic tentacle (
<figureCitation box="[428,503,1186,1212]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,244,1624,1645]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,153,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,153,1603]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9: External anatomy of a dried specimen of Brookula pfefferi Powell, 1951 (ZSM Mol 20021687). A, right anterior­lateral view. B, detail of the right part of the foot, showing the epipodial tentacles and ciliar fringe. C, dorso­frontal view. D, multispiral operculum. E, frontal view. F, detail of figure 1 C, showing the right cephalic tentacle with the numerous sensory papillae. Scale bars A, C – E 100 µm, B, F 10 µm. cl – cilia; ct – cephalic tentacle; ept – epipodial tentacle; f – foot; fl – foot lappet; h – head; op – operculum; sn – snout; sp – sensory papillae; * – most probable the penis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/183713/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">
Figs 
<number box="[488,503,1186,1212]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
A, C, E; marked with “*”) we detected a structure, which could be a penis, but also requires confirmation by histology.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,466,1932]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">
Examination of the shell by SEM showed that the the inner shell layer of the aperture does not consist of a prismatic nacreous layer as typical for iridescence (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Fuchigami" box="[798,1108,1306,1332]" pageId="12" pageNumber="203" refString="Fuchigami, T. &amp; Sasaki, T. (2005) The shell structure of the Recent Patellogastropoda (Mollusca: Gastropoda). Paleontological Research, 9 (2), 143 - 168." type="journal article" year="2005">
Fuchigami &amp; Sasaki 
<number box="[1045,1108,1306,1332]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,466,1932]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">
<bibRefCitation box="[198,443,1346,1372]" pageId="12" pageNumber="203" refString="Absalao, R. S., Miyaji, C. &amp; Pimenta, A. D. (2001) The genus Brookula Iredale, 1912 (Gastropoda, Trochidae) from Brazil: description of a new species, with notes on other South American species. Zoosystema, 23 (4), 675 - 687." type="journal article">
Absalão 
<emphasis box="[301,359,1347,1372]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[374,435,1346,1372]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="2001.0">2001</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
failed in locate the 
<typeStatus box="[673,775,1346,1372]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Pelseneer, 1903" authorityName="Pelseneer" authorityYear="1903" box="[812,1296,1346,1372]" class="Gastropoda" family="Liotiidae" genus="Cyclostrema" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trochida" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="decussatum">
<emphasis box="[812,1103,1347,1372]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">Cyclostrema decussatum</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Pelseneer" box="[1109,1296,1346,1372]" pageId="12" pageNumber="203" refString="Pelseneer, P. (1903) Mollusques (Amphineures, Gastropodes et Lamellibranches). Resultats du Voyage du S. Y. Belgica en 1897 - 1898 - 1899 sous le commandement de A. de Gerlache de Gomery, Rapports Scientifiques, Zoologie, 1 - 85, pls 1 - 9." type="book chapter" year="1903">
Pelseneer, 
<number box="[1235,1296,1346,1372]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="1903.0">1903</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<bibRefCitation pageId="12" pageNumber="204" refString="Zelaya, D. G., Absalao, R. S. &amp; Pimenta, A. D. (2006) A revision of Benthobrookula Clarke, 1961 (Gastropoda, Trochoidea) in the southwestern Atlantic Ocean. Journal of Molluscan Studies, 72 (1), 77 - 87." type="journal article">
Zelaya 
<emphasis box="[151,211,1387,1412]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[228,290,1386,1412]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="2006.0">2006</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
did not take that species into account. The 
<typeStatus box="[820,923,1386,1412]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">holotype</typeStatus>
of this species should be together with the other Pelseneer 
<typeStatus box="[348,410,1426,1452]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">types</typeStatus>
in the Institut Royal des Sciences Naturelles de 
<collectingCountry box="[1021,1130,1426,1452]" name="Belgium" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">Belgique</collectingCountry>
, Bruxelles, 
<collectingCountry box="[1279,1383,1426,1452]" name="Belgium" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">Belgium</collectingCountry>
, but according to Yves Terryn (Scientific Associate), who searched the collection for it on the authors request, the 
<typeStatus box="[151,202,1506,1532]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">type</typeStatus>
is not to be found. Based on the species’ original descriptions and figures we can not see differences between 
<taxonomicName authority="Pelseneer, 1903" authorityName="Pelseneer" authorityYear="1903" box="[257,703,1546,1572]" class="Gastropoda" genus="Brookula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seguenziida" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="decussata">
<emphasis box="[257,489,1547,1572]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">Brookula decussata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Pelseneer" box="[505,695,1546,1572]" pageId="12" pageNumber="203" refString="Pelseneer, P. (1903) Mollusques (Amphineures, Gastropodes et Lamellibranches). Resultats du Voyage du S. Y. Belgica en 1897 - 1898 - 1899 sous le commandement de A. de Gerlache de Gomery, Rapports Scientifiques, Zoologie, 1 - 85, pls 1 - 9." type="book chapter" year="1903">
Pelseneer, 
<number box="[635,695,1546,1572]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="1903.0">1903</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Powell, 1951" authorityName="Powell" authorityYear="1951" box="[762,1048,1546,1572]" class="Gastropoda" genus="Brookula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seguenziida" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pfefferi">
<emphasis box="[762,881,1547,1572]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">B. pfefferi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Powell" box="[889,1048,1546,1572]" pageId="12" pageNumber="203" refString="Powell, A. W. B. (1951) Antarctic and Subantarctic Mollusca: Pelecypoda and Gastropoda. Discovery Reports, 26, 47 - 196." type="journal article" year="1951">
Powell, 
<number box="[987,1048,1546,1572]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="1951.0">1951</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and consider the latter merely a junior synonym of the former. It is important to point out that 
<taxonomicName authority="Pelseneer, 1903" authorityName="Pelseneer" authorityYear="1903" box="[885,1328,1586,1612]" class="Gastropoda" genus="Brookula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seguenziida" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="decussata">
<emphasis box="[885,1117,1587,1612]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">Brookula decussata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Pelseneer" box="[1132,1320,1586,1612]" pageId="12" pageNumber="203" refString="Pelseneer, P. (1903) Mollusques (Amphineures, Gastropodes et Lamellibranches). Resultats du Voyage du S. Y. Belgica en 1897 - 1898 - 1899 sous le commandement de A. de Gerlache de Gomery, Rapports Scientifiques, Zoologie, 1 - 85, pls 1 - 9." type="book chapter" year="1903">
Pelseneer, 
<number box="[1260,1320,1586,1612]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="1903.0">1903</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
does not “clearly differ from 
<taxonomicName authority="A.H.Clarke, 1961" authorityName="A.H.Clarke" authorityYear="1961" box="[401,685,1627,1652]" class="Gastropoda" family="Seguenzioidea incertae sedis" genus="Benthobrookula" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Vetigastropoda incertae sedis" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pfefferi">
<emphasis box="[401,685,1627,1652]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">Benthobrookula pfefferi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a smaller shell, with fewer, more separated, spiral threads” (
<bibRefCitation author="Zelaya" box="[264,482,1666,1692]" pageId="12" pageNumber="204" refString="Zelaya, D. G., Absalao, R. S. &amp; Pimenta, A. D. (2006) A revision of Benthobrookula Clarke, 1961 (Gastropoda, Trochoidea) in the southwestern Atlantic Ocean. Journal of Molluscan Studies, 72 (1), 77 - 87." type="journal article" year="2006">
Zelaya 
<emphasis box="[354,413,1667,1692]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[420,482,1666,1692]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="2006.0">2006</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, p. 
<number box="[525,556,1666,1692]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="80.0">80</number>
) but is instead really similar (see also 
<bibRefCitation author="Powell" box="[1010,1160,1666,1692]" pageId="12" pageNumber="203" refString="Powell, A. W. B. (1951) Antarctic and Subantarctic Mollusca: Pelecypoda and Gastropoda. Discovery Reports, 26, 47 - 196." type="journal article" year="1951">
Powell 
<number box="[1099,1160,1666,1692]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="1951.0">1951</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, p. 
<number box="[1203,1251,1666,1692]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="104.0">104</number>
). A direct comparision of Pelseneer’s illustration (
<number box="[577,639,1706,1732]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="1903.0">1903</number>
, pl. 
<number box="[694,710,1706,1732]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="5.0">5</number>
, fig. 
<number box="[775,806,1706,1732]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="48.0">48</number>
) with the photo of the 
<typeStatus box="[1087,1190,1706,1732]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Powell, 1951" authorityName="Powell" authorityYear="1951" class="Gastropoda" genus="Brookula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seguenziida" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pfefferi">
<emphasis box="[1234,1437,1707,1732]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">Brookula pfefferi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Powell" box="[151,310,1746,1772]" pageId="12" pageNumber="203" refString="Powell, A. W. B. (1951) Antarctic and Subantarctic Mollusca: Pelecypoda and Gastropoda. Discovery Reports, 26, 47 - 196." type="journal article" year="1951">
Powell, 
<number box="[249,310,1746,1772]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="1951.0">1951</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, available from 
<bibRefCitation author="Zelaya" box="[506,736,1746,1772]" pageId="12" pageNumber="204" refString="Zelaya, D. G., Absalao, R. S. &amp; Pimenta, A. D. (2006) A revision of Benthobrookula Clarke, 1961 (Gastropoda, Trochoidea) in the southwestern Atlantic Ocean. Journal of Molluscan Studies, 72 (1), 77 - 87." type="journal article" year="2006">
Zelaya 
<emphasis box="[595,656,1747,1772]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[673,736,1746,1772]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="2006.0">2006</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 
<number box="[800,814,1746,1772]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="5.0">5</number>
A), does not only show the close similarity but also give the impression that the spiral threads are not “more separated”. In addition, while 
<bibRefCitation box="[1199,1436,1786,1812]" pageId="12" pageNumber="204" refString="Zelaya, D. G., Absalao, R. S. &amp; Pimenta, A. D. (2006) A revision of Benthobrookula Clarke, 1961 (Gastropoda, Trochoidea) in the southwestern Atlantic Ocean. Journal of Molluscan Studies, 72 (1), 77 - 87." type="journal article">
Zelaya 
<emphasis box="[1287,1348,1787,1812]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[1366,1428,1786,1812]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="2006.0">2006</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
gave a maximum size of 
<quantity box="[449,554,1826,1852]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.83" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" unit="mm" value="1.83">1.83 mm</quantity>
for 
<taxonomicName authority="Powell, 1951" authorityName="Powell" authorityYear="1951" box="[603,968,1826,1852]" class="Gastropoda" genus="Brookula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seguenziida" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pfefferi">
<emphasis box="[603,804,1827,1852]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">Brookula pfefferi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Powell" box="[812,968,1826,1852]" pageId="12" pageNumber="203" refString="Powell, A. W. B. (1951) Antarctic and Subantarctic Mollusca: Pelecypoda and Gastropoda. Discovery Reports, 26, 47 - 196." type="journal article" year="1951">
Powell, 
<number box="[909,968,1826,1852]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="1951.0">1951</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<quantity box="[984,1053,1826,1852]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
in the original description!), the maximum shell size for 
<taxonomicName authority="Pelseneer, 1903" authorityName="Pelseneer" authorityYear="1903" box="[440,805,1866,1892]" class="Gastropoda" genus="Brookula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seguenziida" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="decussata">
<emphasis box="[440,591,1867,1892]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="199">B. decussata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Pelseneer" box="[607,797,1866,1892]" pageId="12" pageNumber="203" refString="Pelseneer, P. (1903) Mollusques (Amphineures, Gastropodes et Lamellibranches). Resultats du Voyage du S. Y. Belgica en 1897 - 1898 - 1899 sous le commandement de A. de Gerlache de Gomery, Rapports Scientifiques, Zoologie, 1 - 85, pls 1 - 9." type="book chapter" year="1903">
Pelseneer, 
<number box="[737,797,1866,1892]" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" value="1903.0">1903</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
is originally given as 
<quantity box="[1073,1165,1866,1892]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="199" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
and can thus under no circumstances be defined as “smaller”.
</paragraph>
